ican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from any of various places (in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, and elsewhere) called Woodhouse, or a topographic name for someone who lived at a ‘house in the wood’ (Middle English <i>wode</i>, <i>hous</i>, Old English <i>wudu</i>, <i>hūs</i>).","variant of   Woodiwiss  , from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, which by the 16th century was sometimes written as <i>wodowes</i>, <i>woodose</i>, and <i>wodehouse</i>. The confusion with <i>woodhouse</i> probably arose because both words (and both names) were pronounced /wudus/ or /wudǝs/ in local dialect.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Woodis","meanings":["English:","perhaps a nickname from Old English <i>wuduwāsa</i>‘faun, satyr’.","alternatively, a shortened form of   Woodhouse  ."]},{"name":"Woodiwiss","meanings":["English (mainly Derbyshire and Yorkshire): nickname from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, <i>wodewese</i> (Old English <i>wudewāse</i>) ‘wild man of the woods’. This word was also used to denote a person dressed to represent such a being in a play or pageant. Wodewoses (male and female) were mythical creatures of English and ancient Germanic folklore, akin to the fauns and satyrs of Classical mythology. The surname may also have been acquired by someone who lived and worked in the woods or perhaps by an unusually hairy man."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Francis Woodhouse was born about 1220, in Frettenham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Woodhouse I, was 27 and his mother, Petronilla Clervaux, was 22. He married Alice Pecchi in 1244, in Kimberley, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1220–":"umbes 1220–Surnud","1219–Female":"1219–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1195–1267":"1195–1267","1200–1267":"1200–1267","Abt 1245":"umbes 1245","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","1244":"1244","abt 1219":"umbes 1219","1200":"1200","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1220":"1220","1195":"1195","1219":"1219","Frettenham, Norfolk, England":"Frettenham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1220–":"noin 1220–Kuollut","1219–Female":"1219–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1224–Female":"1224–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1195–1267":"1195–1267","1200–1267":"1200–1267","Abt 1245":"noin 1245","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","1244":"1244","abt 1219":"noin 1219","1200":"1200","Abt 1220":"noin 1220","1220":"1220","1195":"1195","1219":"1219","Frettenham, Norfolk, England":"Frettenham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1220–":"environ 1220–Décédé","1219–Female":"1219–Décédée","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","1224–Female":"12